synchronize

public static <E> SortedCollection<E> synchronize(SortedCollection<E> sortedCollection)
Returns a synchronized (thread-safe) SortedCollection backed by the specified sorted collection. In order to guarantee serial access, it is critical that all access to the backing collection is accomplished through the returned collection.

It is imperative that the user manually synchronize on the returned collection when iterating over it: 

  SortedCollection sortedCollection = Collections3.synchronizedSortedCollection(...);
      ...
  synchronized(sortedCollection) {
     for(Object o: sortedCollection)  // Must be in synchronized block
        foo(o);
  }
Failure to follow this advice may result in non-deterministic behavior.

The returned collection will be serializable if the specified collection is serializable.

Parameters:
sortedCollection - the sorted collection to be "wrapped" in a synchronized sorted collection
Returns:
a synchronized view of the specified sorted collection

synchronize

public static <E> SortedList<E> synchronize(SortedList<E> sortedList)
Returns a synchronized (thread-safe) SortedList backed by the specified sorted list. In order to guarantee serial access, it is critical that all access to the backing list is accomplished through the returned list.

It is imperative that the user manually synchronize on the returned list when iterating over it or its views: 

  SortedList sortedList = Collections3.synchronizedSortedList(...);
      ...
  synchronized(sortedList) {
     for(Object o: sortedList)  // Must be in synchronized block
        foo(o);
  }
or: 
  SortedList sortedList = Collections3.synchronizedSortedList(...);
  List subList = sortedList.subList(...)
      ...
  synchronized(sortedList) { // Note: sortedList not subList
     for(Object o: subList)  // Must be in synchronized block
        foo(o);
  }
Failure to follow this advice may result in non-deterministic behavior.

The returned list will be serializable if the specified list is serializable.

Parameters:
sortedList - the sorted list to be "wrapped" in a synchronized sorted list
Returns:
a synchronized view of the specified sorted list

synchronize

public static <E> Deque<E> synchronize(Deque<E> deque)
Returns a synchronized (thread-safe) Deque backed by the specified deque. In order to guarantee serial access, it is critical that all access to the backing deque is accomplished through the returned deque.

It is imperative that the user manually synchronize on the returned deque when iterating over it: 

  Deque deque = Collections3.synchronizedDeque(...);
      ...
  synchronized(deque) {
     for(Object o: deque)  // Must be in synchronized block
       foo(o);
  }
  
  synchronized(deque) {
  Iterator i = deque.descendingIterator();  // Must be in synchronized block
     while (i.hasNext())
        foo(i.next());
  }
Failure to follow this advice may result in non-deterministic behavior.

The returned deque will be serializable if the specified deque is serializable.

Parameters:
deque - the deque to be "wrapped" in a synchronized deque
Returns:
a synchronized view of the specified deque

synchronize

public static <K,V> BoundedMap<K,V> synchronize(BoundedMap<K,V> boundedMap)
Returns a synchronized (thread-safe) BoundedMap backed by the specified bounded map. In order to guarantee serial access, it is critical that all access to the backing map is accomplished through the returned map (or its views).

Clients must manually synchronize on the returned map when iterating over any of its collection views. 

  BoundedMap boundedMap = Collections3.synchronizedBoundedMap(unsynchronizedBoundedMap);
      ...
  Set set = boundedMap.keySet(); // Needn't be in synchronized block
      ...
  synchronized(boundedMap) { // Note: boundedMap, not set
     for(Object o: set)  // Must be in synchronized block
        foo(o);
  }

The returned bounded map will be serializable if the specified bounded map is serializable.

Parameters:
boundedMap - the specified bounded map to synchronize
Returns:
a synchronized view of the specified BoundedMap

unmodifiable

public static <E> SortedCollection<E> unmodifiable(SortedCollection<? extends E> c)
Returns an unmodifiable view of the specified sorted collection. This method allows modules to provide users with "read-only" access to internal collections. Query operations on the returned collection "read through" to the specified sorted collection, and attempts to modify the returned collection, whether direct or via its iterator, result in an UnsupportedOperationException.

The returned sorted collection does not pass the hashCode and equals operations through to the backing collection, but relies on Object's equals(Object) and hashCode() methods. This is necessary to preserve the contracts of these operations in the case that the backing collection is a set or a list.

The returned collection will be serializable if the specified collection is serializable.

Parameters:
c - the sorted collection for which an unmodifiable view is to be returned
Returns:
an unmodifiable view of the specified sorted collection

unmodifiable

public static <E> SortedList<E> unmodifiable(SortedList<? extends E> l)
Returns an unmodifiable view of the specified sorted list. This method allows modules to provide users with "read-only" access to internal sorted lists. Query operations on the returned list "read through" to the specified list, and attempts to modify the returned sorted list, whether direct or via its iterator, result in an UnsupportedOperationException.

The returned list will be serializable if the specified list is serializable.

Note: The returned list does not implement RandomAccess.

Parameters:
l - the list for which an unmodifiable view is to be returned
Returns:
an unmodifiable view of the specified sorted list

Returns an unmodifiable view of the specified bounded map. This method allows modules to provide users with "read-only" access to internal bounded maps. Query operations on the returned map "read through" to the specified map, and attempts to modify the returned bounded map, whether direct or via its collection views, result in an nsupportedOperationException.

The returned map will be serializable if the specified map is serializable.
